<!-- /News Item Row --><tr>
<td width="33"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=33 height=1 border="0"></td>
<td>
<a name="PQN277770"></a>
<br>
<span class="headline">Absor on Server Populations and Economy</span><br>
<span class="byline">4/4/01, 8:05 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@rpgplanet.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem">In response to a players questions on the official boards about the ideal number of people on a server and the economy in EQ, here is what Absor had to say:<blockquote><i> "Could you please tell us what the average
                          number of players is you think to be OK for a server. I am from Europe and at the moment, on weekends,
                          there are sometimes about 1500 players on my server." </i><br><br>Answer:   Actually, 1,500 is a pretty low number of people on a server. I can't imagine that this was a peak time number.
                          If a server were to have only 1,500 players on at peak times, then during off times it might be nearly impossible to
                          find a group. Though crowding certainly wouldn't be an issue, when the server population gets too low there is a
                          legitimate concern about under population. Though with only 1,500 players on finding more than 10% of them in
                          one zone would be shocking. That's got to be a pretty rare occurrence (not the number of people in Greater
                          Faydark, that's number doesn't surprise me if a server has 2,500 people on line at the time).<br><br>

                          With the addition of Velious (and in relation to your third question), I think 2,500 players on a server at peak times
                          isn't too unreasonable.<br><br>

                          <i> "It seems to me that there is a constant inflation of equipment (and money too?) in the game."</i><br><br>Answer:  I'm not an expert on MUD or MMORG economies, but I'll tell you what I see. Yes, there will be a decrease in the
                          value of items over time in EverQuest. Items don't generally leave the economy. This was a known side effect of
                          the decision to not have items decay or get damaged. For the most part, people don't really enjoy doing
                          maintenance on items. It can become a tedious part of gameplay. And for item decay to really have an effect on
                          the economy, to have it effectively keep prices for items stable, it has to eat up a lot of items. This upsets people
                          and makes gameplay less fun. So given the choice to either have items decay (by whatever method) to 'help' the
                          economy or having them remain as relatively permanent things, the designers of EverQuest decided that relative
                          permanency was the better choice.<br><br>

                          So the relative value of older items, ones that have had more time to become more common, will decrease as time
                          passes. Debates have raged over whether this is a good thing or a bad thing, and they will continue to rage.
                          Personally, I think it's a good thing, as an acceptable alternative to the other options.<br><br>

                        <i> "What is your idea of the development of the server population?"</i><br><br>Answer:  Yes, there is a growing population at the higher levels on mature servers. Similar to the point about item decay,
                          the only way to prevent this 'problem' would be to have levels 'decay' by some means. That's also not really going
                          to be popular with players…<br><br>

                          We've added content for the growing population at those levels. And that helps a lot.</span><br><br>
</td>
<td width="10"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=10 height=1 border="0"></td>
</tr>
<!-- /News Item Row --><tr>
<td width="33"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=33 height=1 border="0"></td>
<td>
<a name="PQN277767"></a>
<br>
<span class="headline">More Brownies!?</span><br>
<span class="byline">4/4/01, 8:01 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@rpgplanet.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem">From the "Developers Corner":<blockquote>Horkin wrote:<br><br><i>

                          One thing that has really bothers me has to do with the baking trade skill. I can deal with the fact that it is
                          not a viable trade skill (no one buys made food unless on a whim), I can deal with the fact that we cannot
                          help with the new baking quests (although I found that insulting, why make everyone else have to do
                          baking when the one time we could have been useful we are without use), but the availability of brownie
                          meat is what really annoys me.<Br><br>

                          As far as I know there are 17 brownies on the face of Norrath, Nillipuss (dead as soon as he pops), 3 in GF,
                          and 13 in LF. The ones in GF, I have tried to hunt, with my ranger, and they do not show up on tracking
                          ever, I stumbled across 4 in 3 hours of actively hunting them only (and not ONE dropped meat). Nillipuss
                          is already spoken for, all the time, which leaves the LF brownies, or as I like to call them, Hell's Fairies.<br><br>

                          The brownies that are NOT at Dis (the brownie home-town) are god-awful, red to a 30th level character
                          (haven't been back for ten levels), and the town is a NIGHTMARE. I have seen 3 50th level characters get
                          wiped out trying to pull one guard. So my very long winded lead in to this yields a few small, simple
                          questions.<br><br>

                          Was it designed that I should need a Vox-hunting platoon of uber-goons in order for me to bake a simple
                          birthday cake? And, if I do find such a thug-squad, why is it that brownie meat does not drop EVERY single
                          time? What, do they self-destruct when they figure out they will be killed? Is it possible to get brownie
                          meat put into Mornin's Inventory in Thurgadin? Please, I am desperate here, I NEED to bake, it's in me
                          soul, and I am bottlenecked at cakes, 'tis enough to drive a sane gnome to drinking and consorting with
                          gnolls!<br><br></i>

                          Absor replies:  Brownies are tiny little things, perhaps they just don't have a lot of meat on their bones and you have to find a
                          really fat one to get any usable quantity of meat…<br><br>

                          Or, maybe we need to make it more available. I'm not sure that adding it to a vendor is the solution. I'll send your
                          request to the team.  

                          Thanks.</blockquote>
</span><br><br>
</td>
<td width="10"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=10 height=1 border="0"></td>
</tr>
<!-- /News Item Row --><tr>
<td width="33"><img src="/images/clear.gif" width=33 height=1 border="0"></td>
<td>
<a name="PQN277763"></a>
<br>
<span class="headline">Patch Message</span><br>
<span class="byline">4/4/01, 7:51 PST | <a href="mailto:kwill@rpgplanet.com">Kwill</a></span><br><br>
<span class="newsitem"> ** New and Changed Features **<br><br>

                 - Guild Message of the Day. Guild Officers and Leaders will be able to type /guildmotd to set up
                 a Guild Message of the Day (GMotD). From then on any time a member of that guild logs in they
                 will see the message with the name of the message sender added at the front, so you will know
                 who sent the message. Any guild member will also be able to read the GMotD by typing just
                 /guildmotd and the message will be displayed again. The GMotD will be erased if the server
                 comes down, however. You will have to reset the GMotD when the server comes back up.<br><br>

                 - /assist changed and improved. It should be much more reliable now. It also will target
                 whatever the assisted person has targeted. The assisted person does not need to have
                 auto-attack on for /assist to work.<br><br>

                 - Fixed a problem with /corpse that kept it from working on corpses that were too far above or
                 below you.<br><br>


                 ** Skill Change **<br><br>

                 - Foraging changed so that if you are getting the hungry and thirsty messages, your next
                 successful forage will always be drink or food. We have also decreased the chance of foraging
                 fishing grubs a bit and increased the chance that you will forage water.<br><br>


                 ** Spell Changes **<br><br>

                 - Acumen now overwrites See Invisible.<br><br>

                 - Translocate now has the proper spell gem.<br><br>


                 ** Bug Fix **<br><br>

                 - Fixed many crash problems for Windows 2000 users. This fix will most likely also aid some folks
                 that are not using Windows 2000 that are having problems.<br><br>


                 ** Item Changes **<br><br>

                 - Velious racial plate helm quests have been added that will allow you to 'trade in' your existing
                 helms for ones with textures. We have decided to allow the players (or their characters) to
                 chose whether they wish to have the new helmet textures or to continue to use helmets that
                 show no graphics.<br><br>

                 - Five and ten charge versions of Potions of the Bone Field have been added.<br><br>

                 - Kilva's Skin of Flame potion has been changed. It no longer has the same effect as the Kilva's
                 Blistering Flesh potion.<br><br>

                 - Removed the tinting from Dark Forge and Resonant armors. Tinting was never really intended
                 to be on those pieces and, frankly, they look better without it.<br><br>


                 ** Miscellaneous Items **<br><br>

                 - Reduced the 'bottleneck' for getting Howling Stone keys by increasing the availability of one
                 of the quest items.<br><br>

                 - Erudite guards will now be much less friendly to Kobolds.<br><br>

                 - Vendors are once again selling the Coldain Tanner's Kit.<br.<br>


                 ** 'Combine' container changes **<br><br>

                 We've made a change to 'combine' containers. In order to prevent people from accidentally
                 destroying items, all containers with a 'combine' button will not combine any items that do not
                 form a complete recipe. This will be a huge boon to craftspeople all across Norrath. But this
                 removes the only drawback to using trade containers as backpacks. Their reduced weight and
                 often greater carrying capacity made them more desirable as bags, with the compensating risk
                 that you might just lose something if you made a mistake.<br><br>

                 We will be increasing the weight of portable 'combine' containers somewhat. Where some of
                 these containers weighed under 1 pound, they will now weigh as much as 4 pounds for the
                 largest sewing kit.<br><br>

                 Along with this we are making a change to tailor made backpacks. In case you didn't know,
                 most tailor made packs have a built in weight reduction of 5%. We are raising that to 10%. We
                 will also be displaying the weight reduction of all containers with the information shown on a
                 right click.<br><br>

                 - The EverQuest Team </span><br><br>
</td>
